  "text": "Stack protection mechanisms in LLVM are implemented across multiple components to protect against buffer overflow attacks:\n\n1. **StackProtector Pass** (llvm/lib/CodeGen/StackProtector.cpp, llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/StackProtector.h):\n   - The main pass is `StackProtectorPass` (new pass manager) and `StackProtector` (legacy pass)\n   - Inserts stack protector checks into function prologues and epilogues\n   - Primary class: `StackProtector` implements `FunctionPass` interface\n   - Contains `SSPLayoutAnalysis` which determines which functions need stack protectors\n   - Key functions: `InsertStackProtectors()` inserts prologue/epilogue code, `CreateFailBB()` creates the failure block that calls `__stack_chk_fail()`\n   - The pass stores a random canary value onto the stack before local variables are allocated and checks it upon function exit\n\n2. **SafeStack Pass** (llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStack.cpp, llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/SafeStack.h):\n   - The main pass is `SafeStackPass` which separates stack allocations into safe and unsafe stacks\n   - Primary class: `SafeStack` in SafeStack.cpp handles the transformation\n   - Splits the stack into: (1) safe stack (kept as-is for LLVM backend), (2) unsafe stack (explicitly allocated through runtime)\n   - Uses `SafeStackLayout` to compute the layout of unsafe stack frames\n   - Identifies allocas that can be safely accessed and those that cannot\n\n3. **SafeStackLayout** (llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStackLayout.cpp, llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStackLayout.h):\n   - Primary class: `StackLayout` in namespace `safestack`\n   - Computes the memory layout of unsafe stack frames\n   - Manages object placement with alignment and lifetime considerations\n   - Provides methods: `addObject()`, `computeLayout()`, `getObjectOffset()`, `getFrameSize()`\n\n4. **StackSafetyAnalysis** (llvm/lib/Analysis/StackSafetyAnalysis.cpp, llvm/include/llvm/Analysis/StackSafetyAnalysis.h):\n   - Function-level analysis: `StackSafetyAnalysis` with `StackSafetyInfo` result\n   - Global analysis: `StackSafetyGlobalAnalysis` with `StackSafetyGlobalInfo` result\n   - Detects allocas and arguments with provably safe accesses\n   - Determines which stack accesses are safe (in-bounds and within lifetime)\n   - Works with scalar evolution to prove safety of memory operations\n\n5. **BoundsChecking Pass** (llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/BoundsChecking.cpp, llvm/include/llvm/Transforms/Instrumentation/BoundsChecking.h):\n   - Primary class: `BoundsCheckingPass` in Instrumentation directory\n   - Instruments code to perform runtime bounds checking on loads, stores, and memory intrinsics\n   - Adds overflow checks for memory accesses\n   - Complements stack protection by detecting memory access violations at runtime\n\n**Runtime Support**:\nThe `__stack_chk_fail()` function is not implemented in LLVM but is referenced throughout the codebase. It is a C runtime library function (typically provided by libc) that is called when the stack canary check fails, terminating the program to prevent exploitation. The canary value itself (`__stack_chk_guard`) is typically provided by the system's C library or operating system.\n\n**Integration**:\nThese mechanisms work together: StackProtector inserts canary checks, SafeStack separates allocations to reduce vulnerability surface, SafeStackLayout optimizes the unsafe stack layout, StackSafetyAnalysis provides information about which accesses are safe, and BoundsChecking adds runtime checks for comprehensive protection."
}

